Body:
For the story of the tribe of Thamud, given here as an
				illustration of man's potential wickedness, see {7:73-79}
				and the corresponding notes.

A reference to the terms in which Moses was to - and
				apparently did - announce his mission (see verse {16}
				above).

This connects with the opening sentence of verse {9}
				above: "Would you indeed deny Him who has created...",
				etc.

For the story of these two ancient tribes, see {7:65-79}
				and the corresponding notes, in particular [48] and [56];
				also {26:123-158}.

Sc., "unless God wills to reprieve them": see the last
				paragraph of <a href='qa:6.128'>6:128</a> and the corresponding note [114];
				also the hadith quoted in note [10] on <a href='qa:40.12'>40:12</a>.

See verse {30} above, as well as the corresponding notes;
				also <a href='qa:3.19'>3:19</a> - "the only [true] religion in the sight of
				God is [man's] self-surrender unto Him".

They considered him "weak-minded" because he expected
				them to give up their traditional beliefs and deities;
				and a "liar", because he claimed to be a prophet of God.

I.e., "when it is too late" (Tabari, Zamakhshari, Razi;
				my interpolation at the beginning of this sentence is
				based on these authorities).
